sec.p:
In a controlled greenhouse setting, two peanut seeds were planted in each of four 4-inch plastic pots filled with nutrient-rich, sterilized soil. A temperature range of 30–24 °C, together with plenty of sunlight and humidity, was available to the plants. The plants had to have grown for 30 days to provide the treatments. There were three pots for each treatment. Five leaves (20 leaflets) were inoculated by soaking them in 10 mL of C. arachidicola (Ca) and 10 mL of MU-10. OP broth was mixed with 10 mL of C. arachidicola (Ca + MU-10. OP), and 10 mL of MU-10. NOP broth was mixed with 10 mL of C. arachidicola (Ca + MU = 10NOP), and 10 mL of commercial fungicide (tebuconazole) (CF) was mixed with 10 mL of C. arachidicola (CK), respectively. The following formula calculates disease incidence and disease control efficiency [4]. In the first step, the disease incidence percentage was determined. The total number of infected leaflets was divided by the total number of leaflets and multiplied by 100. Therefore, disease incidence is directly equal to disease control.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
